This is a [general introduction](/Wikipedia:INFOPAGES) for visitors to Wikipedia. For aspiring contributors, also see this [guide](/Wikipedia:Contributing_to_Wikipedia) and [tutorial](/Help:Introduction). For other uses, see [Wikipedia:Wikipedia (disambiguation)](/Wikipedia:Wikipedia_(disambiguation)).

Imagine a world in which every single person on the planet is given free access to the sum of all human knowledge. That's what we're doing. — [Jimmy Wales](/Jimmy_Wales)

[Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) is a [free online encyclopedia](/Wikipedia:Free_encyclopedia) that anyone can edit, and [millions already have](/Wikipedia:Wikipedians).

[Wikipedia's purpose](/Wikipedia:Purpose) is to benefit readers by presenting information on all branches of [knowledge](/Knowledge). Hosted by the [Wikimedia Foundation](/Wikipedia:Wikimedia_Foundation), Wikipedia consists of [freely editable](/Help:Editing) content, with articles that usually contain numerous links guiding readers to more information.

[Written collaboratively](/Collaborative_writing) by volunteers known as [Wikipedians](/Wikipedia_community), Wikipedia articles can be edited by anyone with [Internet access](/Internet_access), except in [limited cases](/Wikipedia:Protection_policy) in which [editing](/Editing) is restricted to prevent [disruption](/Wikipedia:Disruption) or [vandalism](/Wikipedia:VAND). Since its creation on [January 15, 2001](/Wikipedia_Day), it has grown into the world's [largest](/Wikipedia:Size_of_Wikipedia) reference [website](/Website), attracting over a billion visitors each month. Wikipedia currently has more than sixty-six million articles in [more than 300 languages](/Special:SiteMatrix), including 7,110,644 articles in [English](/English_language), with 291,214 active contributors in the past month.

A short video explaining how Wikipedia works

Wikipedia's fundamental principles are summarized in its [five pillars](/Wikipedia:Five_pillars). While the [Wikipedia community](/Wikipedia_community) has developed many [policies and guidelines](/Wikipedia:Policies_and_guidelines), new editors do not need to be familiar with them before they start contributing.

[Anyone](/Wikipedia:Who_writes_Wikipedia%3F) can [edit](/Help:Editing) Wikipedia's text, data, references, and images. The quality of content is more important than the expertise of who contributes it. Wikipedia's content must conform with its [policies](/Wikipedia:Editing_policy), including being [verifiable](/Wikipedia:Verifiable) by published [reliable sources](/Wikipedia:Reliable_sources). Contributions based on [personal opinions](/Wikipedia:Neutral_point_of_view), beliefs, or personal experiences, [unreviewed research](/Wikipedia:Original_research), libellous material, and [copyright violations](/Wikipedia:Copyright_violations) are not allowed, and will not remain. Wikipedia's software makes it easy to reverse errors, and experienced [editors](/Wikipedia_editor) [watch](/Wikipedia:Watchlist) and [patrol](/Wikipedia:Recent_changes_patrol) bad edits.

[Wikipedia differs from printed references in important ways](/Wikipedia:NOTPAPER). Anyone can instantly improve it, add quality information, remove misinformation, and fix errors and [vandalism](/Wikipedia:Vandalism). Since Wikipedia is continually updated, encyclopedic articles on major news events appear within minutes.

For over 24 years, editors have volunteered their time and talents to create history's most comprehensive encyclopedia while providing references and other resources to researchers worldwide (see [Researching with Wikipedia](/Wikipedia:Researching_with_Wikipedia)). In summary, Wikipedia has tested the [wisdom of the crowd](/Wisdom_of_the_crowd) since 2001 and has found that it succeeds.

To start editing, simply click the Edit or Edit source  button, or the pencil icon  , at the top of any [non-protected](/Wikipedia:Protection_policy) Wikipedia page or section.


